      Journalism
   =20
 =20

One thing that I   think about sometimes is the similarity between journali=
sm and insider trading. Consider: You are in the business of finding out th=
ings about companies that nobody else knows, so you spend your time develop=
ing sources at those companies who will tell you things. If their company h=
as a new product coming out, or is about to announce a merger, or has been =
doing fraud, they call you to tell you before anyone else knows.
Sometimes they tell you things just because you ask, and they are indiscree=
t. Sometimes they tell you things out of a sense of public-spiritedness: Th=
ey think that what they know should be known more broadly. Sometimes they t=
ell you things out of a sense of grievance: They are mad at their bosses an=
d want to leak information. Sometimes they tell you things because you are =
friends:=C2=A0You have done such a good job of developing=C2=A0relationship=
s that your sources think of you as a personal friend, not just a transacti=
onal counterparty. Sometimes there is some amount of favor-trading involved=
: You get information from them, and in exchange you give=C2=A0them somethi=
ng that they want. Perhaps that is also information: You give them news or =
gossip about their firm or industry that you got from other sources. Or per=
haps you can give them career advice. Or maybe you just buy them lunch, or =
drinks. Maybe you pay them cash!
  [1]
 Often, of course, their motives are mixed; they tell you stuff out of publ=
ic-spiritedness and grievance and friendship and favor-trading and careless=
ness all at once.
What do you do with this information? Here are three possibilities
  [2]
:
=09You work at a newspaper, you write up a story containing your sources=E2=
=80=99 secret information, and you publish it on your website and in your p=
rint newspaper.=C2=A0=09You work at a hedge fund, and you trade on your sou=
rces=E2=80=99 information: You buy ahead of the merger announcement, sell a=
head of the accounting fraud, whatever.=09You work at a very=C2=A0small and=
 odd=C2=A0newspaper, one that charges $1 million a year for a subscription =
and that has only five subscribers, all of them hedge funds. You write up a=
 story containing your sources=E2=80=99 secret information, you put it in y=
our newspaper, and you send it to your subscribers, who then trade on it.

Option 1 is=C2=A0called =E2=80=9Cjournalism.=E2=80=9D
  [3]
=C2=A0It is generally considered a good thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0the public has=
 a right to know secret stuff, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and in the US it is prot=
ected by the First Amendment.
  [4]
=C2=A0Of course some of the readers of your newspaper will trade on what yo=
u publish, but that=E2=80=99s fine; journalism can move markets.
Option 2 is=C2=A0usually=C2=A0called =E2=80=9Cinsider trading,=E2=80=9D and=
 in most cases, in the US, it is illegal.
  [5]

Option 3 is a gray area! It seems clear to me that if you have one subscrib=
er and=C2=A0a million-dollar subscription, that=E2=80=99s insider trading: =
You=C2=A0work for a hedge fund, but you have an obfuscatory job title. Prob=
ably at five subscribers it is still insider trading.
  [6]
 On the other hand, at a million subscribers and a $200 subscription, you a=
re clearly a journalist: Publishing a story behind a paywall, to paying cus=
tomers who get it before everyone else, still counts as journalism.
Disclosure! Bloomberg News publishes many stories to Bloomberg Terminal sub=
scribers before they are on the website. But that is still journalism.
I think that probably the dividing line between =E2=80=9Cjournalism=E2=80=
=9D and =E2=80=9Cinsider trading=E2=80=9D is, like, some number of subscrib=
ers? The number is not that high. I think that sending a newsletter to 50 s=
ubscribers, 95% of them hedge funds, for $50,000 each per year,=C2=A0probab=
ly looks more like journalism than like insider trading. Whereas five subsc=
ribers is insider trading. But I am just making that up and oh boy is it no=
t legal advice.
Anyway  the Financial Times reports:

A group of veteran US financial journalists is teaming up with investors to=
 launch a trading firm that is designed to trade on market-moving news unea=
rthed by its own investigative reporting.
The business, founded by investor Nathaniel Brooks Horwitz and writer Sam K=
oppelman, would comprise two entities: a trading fund and a group of analys=
ts and journalists producing stories based on publicly available material, =
according to several people familiar with the matter.
The fund would place trades before articles were published, and then publis=
h its research and trading thesis, they said, but would not trade on inform=
ation that was not publicly available.
The start-up, called Hunterbrook, had raised $10mn in seed funding and is t=
argeting a $100mn launch for its fund, according to two people involved. =
=E2=80=9CWatchdog=E2=80=9D was a name floated early on for the news arm. =
=E2=80=A6
In an early message to potential investors, seen by the Financial Times, Ho=
rwitz said the investment fund would get =E2=80=9Cunique access=E2=80=9D to=
 articles before they are published. =E2=80=9CRather than try to predict or=
 react to events, we time trades on news we break ourselves,=E2=80=9D he wr=
ote, styling the venture as =E2=80=9Cthe first trading fund driven by a glo=
bal publication=E2=80=9D.
The reporting team =E2=80=94 which Horwitz=E2=80=99s email said would inclu=
de journalists who have worked for the WSJ, BBC and Barron=E2=80=99s, as we=
ll as =E2=80=9Cintel analysts=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 aims to publish market-mov=
ing investigative pieces =E2=80=9Clike Bloomberg=E2=80=9D, but with no adve=
rtisements or subscription paywall.

I don=E2=80=99t know! The two claims here are:
=09You =E2=80=9Cbreak=C2=A0news=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cpublish market-moving=
 investigative pieces =E2=80=98like Bloomberg,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D which mean=
s that you employ reporters who get sources to=C2=A0tell you stuff that is =
not already public, and=09You produce =E2=80=9Cstories based on publicly av=
ailable material.=E2=80=9D

There is some=C2=A0overlap between those categories. Sometimes you can, lik=
e, read a company=E2=80=99s securities filings closely, notice something we=
ird, publish a story saying =E2=80=9CCompany X admits Y in its annual repor=
t,=E2=80=9D and say you have broken news and moved the market with your inv=
estigation of public documents, without using =E2=80=9Cinformation that was=
 not publicly available.=E2=80=9D Or=C2=A0Freedom of Information Act reques=
ts=C2=A0are a common journalistic tool that can=C2=A0get you information th=
at is technically public and yet known only to you. You can buy a company=
=E2=80=99s product and take it apart and see if it=E2=80=99s made of cobweb=
s. Other things. Still I feel like a lot of investigative journalism involv=
es calling sources and asking them to tell you stuff that isn=E2=80=99t pub=
lic? And then if you publish it that=E2=80=99s fine, that=E2=80=99s great, =
that=E2=80=99s classic journalism. But if you trade on it first, that=E2=80=
=99s riskier.
  [7]

Of course, there is another obvious comparison for this model. What is, lik=
e,  Hindenburg Research if not an investigative reporting organization that=
 trades on its investigations before it publishes them? The whole model of =
activist short selling looks pretty much like this: You try to find public =
companies that are frauds, you investigate them, you short their stock, and=
 then you publish your investigation, hoping that it will drive the stock d=
own. Carson Block, another activist short seller, =E2=80=9Cdescribes what h=
e does as =E2=80=98investigative journalism married to a different business=
 model=E2=80=99 and is trying to rebrand activist shorts as =E2=80=98journa=
list investors.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D
The risks of that model are pretty well known. For one thing, yes, insider =
trading; some short sellers try to=C2=A0rely mostly on public information t=
o avoid being accused of insider trading.
  [8]
=C2=A0For another thing, activist short sellers are=C2=A0constantly=C2=A0ac=
cused of market manipulation: It is just widely assumed that, if you bet ag=
ainst a company=E2=80=99s stock and then=C2=A0publish bad stuff about the c=
ompany, you are doing something fraudulent and manipulative. If you publish=
