   =20
      PE and rates
   =20
 =20

If you had asked me a few years ago, at an extremely high level of generali=
ty, how much the two tranches of a leveraged buyout should get paid =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0like, how much interest lenders should charge for lending money to=
 private equity portfolio companies, and how much the equity investors in t=
he private equity funds should expect to make =E2=80=94=C2=A0I guess I woul=
d have thrown out numbers like, I don=E2=80=99t know, 7% and 15%? No scienc=
e to that. But high-yield debt in like the mid-to-high single digits, and p=
rivate equity internal rates of return in the low-to-mid teens? Kind of? Bl=
ackstone Group Inc., for instance, lists the investment records for its pri=
vate equity funds, and many of the more recent ones have those sorts of tee=
n-ish IRRs.
Then interest rates went up a lot very quickly, though. Here is Blackstone =
founder Steve Schwarzman at a conference in September:
=E2=80=9CIf you can earn 12 per cent, maybe 13 per cent on a really good da=
y in senior secured bank debt, what else do you want to do in life?,=E2=80=
=9D Schwarzman told the conference. =E2=80=9CIf you are living in a no-grow=
th economy and somebody can give you 12, 13 per cent with almost no prospec=
t of loss, that=E2=80=99s about the best thing you can do.=E2=80=9D
Blackstone, and all the other private equity firms, are now big in private =
credit, which includes (among other things) lending money to leveraged buyo=
uts. That used to pay a little; now it pays 12% or 13%. Meanwhile if you wo=
rk in private=C2=A0equity, and you got used to mid-teen IRRs, you have a pr=
oblem. Really two problems:
=09You are paying a lot more for debt, which is going to eat into your retu=
rns.=09Even if you do get mid-teen returns, that just doesn=E2=80=99t look =
very good compared to earning 13% on the=C2=A0safe=C2=A0tranche of the deal=
.

=E2=80=9CWhat else do you want to do in life,=E2=80=9D says your boss, abou=
t private=C2=A0credit, which makes you nervous about your=C2=A0job in priva=
te=C2=A0equity.
Here is a Financial Times article titled =E2=80=9CPrivate equity: higher ra=
tes start to pummel dealmakers.=E2=80=9D It begins like this:

In early March, Carlyle Group appeared close to a takeover that valued heal=
thcare software company Cotiviti at $15bn. It was just the sort of audaciou=
s deal that large private equity firms have been pulling off for much of th=
e past decade.
More than a dozen private lenders, including the credit arms of Blackstone,=
 Apollo Global, Ares and HPS, were ready to sign off on a record $5.5bn pri=
vate loan that would have put Carlyle in control of Cotiviti.
But the process dragged on for weeks. According to more than a dozen people=
 involved in the transaction, the key hold-up was a stunning setback in an =
industry managing $3.3tn of assets: Carlyle, one of the most powerful priva=
te equity firms, had been unable to raise all of its roughly $3bn equity co=
mmitment from investors.
The yield on the debt financing, around 12 per cent at the time, would have=
 been approaching the return Carlyle was hoping to earn, stifling interest =
from potential investors, according to one person involved in the deal. Whe=
n Carlyle attempted to renegotiate the $15bn valuation, Veritas Capital, th=
e existing private equity owner, walked away from the sale.

Feels like there is going to be a lot of that.

