      MicroStrategy
   =20
 =20

For a long time, there has been demand from investors for a product that is=
 =E2=80=9CBitcoin, but a US-listed stock.=E2=80=9D The most straightforward=
 way to satisfy that demand would be with a Bitcoin exchange-traded fund: Y=
ou put some Bitcoins in a pot, you issue shares of the pot, you let people =
exchange Bitcoins for shares or shares for Bitcoins in a way that keeps the=
 price of the shares in line with the price of Bitcoin. The US Securities a=
nd Exchange Commission, for mostly bad reasons, has refused to allow anyone=
 to do this. The SEC got sued over this,   and lost, and everyone anticipat=
es that there will soon be Bitcoin ETFs.
But for a long time there weren=E2=80=99t, so that demand has been=C2=A0sat=
isfied by imperfect substitutes. One substitute is   Bitcoin=C2=A0futures=
=C2=A0ETFs, which are like Bitcoin ETFs but use derivatives and have some s=
lippage. Another substitute is the Grayscale Bitcoin Trust, which is like a=
 Bitcoin ETF except that you can=E2=80=99t take Bitcoins=C2=A0out=C2=A0(you=
 can't trade in your shares for Bitcoins), so the price of the shares does =
not stay in line with the price of Bitcoin. A third substitute is MicroStra=
tegy Inc., a publicly traded US software company that also just owns a lot =
of Bitcoin. It=E2=80=99s a publicly traded pot of Bitcoin with a software c=
ompany attached to it, which is a sillier way to invest in Bitcoin than jus=
t a publicly traded pot of Bitcoin=C2=A0without=C2=A0a software company att=
ached, but better than nothing.
  [11]

It seems to me that a lot of these substitutes are lucrative (for the peopl=
e offering them) but temporary. The most interesting fact about Grayscale i=
s probably that it charges a 2% fee on its pot of Bitcoins. If it converts =
into an ETF =E2=80=94=C2=A0as it plans to, once the SEC approves =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0it probably can=E2=80=99t keep that up; ETF fees are much lower, and =
if Grayscale keeps charging 2%, its shareholders will take their Bitcoins b=
ack (as soon as they=E2=80=99re allowed to). And   then there is MicroStrat=
egy:

MicroStrategy Inc. Chairman Michael Saylor=E2=80=99s strategy of buying Bit=
coin may be coming into question as the advent of exchange-traded funds hol=
ding the largest cryptocurrency appears imminent. =E2=80=A6
Now with the US Securities and Exchange Commission seeming likely to approv=
e ETFs that invest directly in Bitcoin after a key court loss earlier this =
year, investors and analysts are beginning to debate whether MicroStrategy=
=E2=80=99s shares will continue to command a premium. Even MicroStrategy, w=
hich releases quarterly results later Wednesday, has raised the question in=
 a recent filing.
=E2=80=9CTo the extent that our Class A common stock is viewed as an altern=
ative-to-Bitcoin investment vehicle and trades at a premium to the value of=
 our Bitcoin holdings, that premium may also be eliminated, causing the pri=
ce of our Class A common stock to decline,=E2=80=9D the Tysons Corner, Virg=
inia-based company wrote in an Aug. 1 filing.

In a world where a publicly traded pot of Bitcoins is a rare and inaccessib=
le thing, people will pay up for a weird one. In a world in which it is nor=
mal and straightforward, they won=E2=80=99t.

