<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Journalism</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/33220840.283413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMjYvZnR4LXNwZW50LWJpZy1vbi1jZWxlYnJpdH=
k_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlP=
W5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMTAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB8ca1ae35" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  think about sometimes</a> is the simi=
larity between journalism and insider trading. Consider: You are in the bus=
iness of finding out things about companies that nobody else knows, so you =
spend your time developing sources at those companies who will tell you thi=
ngs. If their company has a new product coming out, or is about to announce=
 a merger, or has been doing fraud, they call you to tell you before anyone=
 else knows.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes they tell you things just because yo=
u ask, and they are indiscreet. Sometimes they tell you things out of a sen=
se of public-spiritedness: They think that what they know should be known m=
ore broadly. Sometimes they tell you things out of a sense of grievance: Th=
ey are mad at their bosses and want to leak information. Sometimes they tel=
l you things because you are <em>friends:=C2=A0</em>You have done such a go=
od job of developing=C2=A0relationships that your sources think of you as a=
 personal friend, not just a transactional counterparty. Sometimes there is=
 some amount of favor-trading involved: You get information from them, and =
in exchange you give=C2=A0them something that they want. Perhaps that is al=
so information: You give them news or gossip about their firm or industry t=
hat you got from other sources. Or perhaps you can give them career advice.=
 Or maybe you just buy them lunch, or drinks. Maybe you pay them cash!<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> Often, of course, their motives are mixed; they tell you stuff out of =
public-spiritedness and grievance and friendship and favor-trading and care=
lessness all at once.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What do you do with this information? Here are=
 three possibilities<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You work at a newspaper, you write up=
 a story containing your sources=E2=80=99 secret information, and you publi=
sh it on your website and in your print newspaper.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You work at a hedge fund, and you trade on your so=
urces=E2=80=99 information: You buy ahead of the merger announcement, sell =
ahead of the accounting fraud, whatever.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">You work at a very=C2=A0<em>small </em>and <em>odd=C2=A0</em>newspap=
er, one that charges $1 million a year for a subscription and that has only=
 five subscribers, all of them hedge funds. You write up a story containing=
 your sources=E2=80=99 secret information, you put it in your newspaper, an=
d you send it to your subscribers, who then trade on it.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Option 1 is=C2=A0called =E2=80=9Cjournalism.=
=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It is generally considered a good thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0the public=
 has a right to know secret stuff, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and in the US it is =
protected by the First Amendment.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
>
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Of course some of the readers of your newspaper will trade on wha=
t you publish, but that=E2=80=99s fine; journalism can move markets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Option 2 is=C2=A0<em>usually</em>=C2=A0called =
=E2=80=9Cinsider trading,=E2=80=9D and in most cases, in the US, it is ille=
gal.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Option 3 is a gray area! It seems clear to me =
that if you have <em>one</em> subscriber and=C2=A0a million-dollar subscrip=
tion, that=E2=80=99s insider trading: You=C2=A0work for a hedge fund, but y=
ou have an obfuscatory job title. Probably at five subscribers it is still =
insider trading.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a> On the other hand, at a million subscribers and a $200 subscription, y=
ou are clearly a <em>journalist</em>: Publishing a story behind a paywall, =
to paying customers who get it before everyone else, still counts as journa=
lism.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Disclosure! Bloomberg News publishes many stor=
ies to Bloomberg Terminal subscribers before they are on the website. But t=
hat is still journalism.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that probably the dividing line betwee=
n =E2=80=9Cjournalism=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cinsider trading=E2=80=9D is, li=
ke, some number of subscribers? The number is not that high. I think that s=
ending a newsletter to 50 subscribers, 95% of them hedge funds, for $50,000=
 each per year,=C2=A0<em>probably </em>looks more like journalism than like=
 insider trading. Whereas five subscribers is insider trading. But I am jus=
t making that up and oh boy is it not legal advice.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/33220840.283413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvODU1M=
GQxZmUtNTY5Yi00NzljLWI1YjMtNjIyNzE2ZWRhMTY3/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5310b9=
02" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> the Financial Times reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A group of veteran US financial journalists is=
 teaming up with investors to launch a trading firm that is designed to tra=
de on market-moving news unearthed by its own investigative reporting.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The business, founded by investor Nathaniel Br=
ooks Horwitz and writer Sam Koppelman, would comprise two entities: a tradi=
ng fund and a group of analysts and journalists producing stories based on =
publicly available material, according to several people familiar with the =
matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fund would place trades before articles we=
re published, and then publish its research and trading thesis, they said, =
but would not trade on information that was not publicly available.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The start-up, called Hunterbrook, had raised $=
10mn in seed funding and is targeting a $100mn launch for its fund, accordi=
ng to two people involved. =E2=80=9CWatchdog=E2=80=9D was a name floated ea=
rly on for the news arm. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In an early message to potential investors, se=
en by the Financial Times, Horwitz said the investment fund would get =E2=
=80=9Cunique access=E2=80=9D to articles before they are published. =E2=80=
=9CRather than try to predict or react to events, we time trades on news we=
 break ourselves,=E2=80=9D he wrote, styling the venture as =E2=80=9Cthe fi=
rst trading fund driven by a global publication=E2=80=9D.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The reporting team =E2=80=94 which Horwitz=E2=
=80=99s email said would include journalists who have worked for the WSJ, B=
BC and Barron=E2=80=99s, as well as =E2=80=9Cintel analysts=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94 aims to publish market-moving investigative pieces =E2=80=9Clike Bloomb=
erg=E2=80=9D, but with no advertisements or subscription paywall.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know! The two claims here are:=
</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You =E2=80=9Cbreak=C2=A0news=E2=80=9D=
 and =E2=80=9Cpublish market-moving investigative pieces =E2=80=98like Bloo=
mberg,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D which means that you employ reporters who get sour=
ces to=C2=A0<em>tell you stuff that is not already public</em>, and</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You produce =E2=80=9Cstories based on pub=
licly available material.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is some<em>=C2=A0</em>overlap between th=
ose categories. Sometimes you can, like, read a company=E2=80=99s securitie=
s filings closely, notice something weird, publish a story saying =E2=80=9C=
Company X admits Y in its annual report,=E2=80=9D and say you have broken n=
ews and moved the market with your investigation of public documents, witho=
ut using =E2=80=9Cinformation that was not publicly available.=E2=80=9D Or=
=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33220840.283=
413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZm9pYS5nb3Yv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfdd6d184" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>Freedom of Information Act requests</a>=C2=A0are a common journalistic too=
l that can=C2=A0get you information that is technically public and yet know=
n only to you. You can buy a company=E2=80=99s product and take it apart an=
d see if it=E2=80=99s made of cobwebs. Other things. Still I feel like a lo=
t of investigative journalism involves calling sources and asking them to t=
ell you stuff that isn=E2=80=99t public? And then if you publish it that=E2=
=80=99s fine, that=E2=80=99s great, that=E2=80=99s classic journalism. But =
if you trade on it first, that=E2=80=99s riskier.<a class=3D"footnote-index=
" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display=
: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course, there is another obvious comparison=
 for this model. What is, like, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/33220840.283413/aHR0cHM6Ly9oaW5kZW5idXJncmVzZWFyY2guY29tLw/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB237c16d5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Hindenburg Research</a> if not an=
 investigative reporting organization that trades on its investigations bef=
ore it publishes them? The whole model of activist short selling looks pret=
ty much like this: You try to find public companies that are frauds, you in=
vestigate them, you short their stock, and then you publish your investigat=
ion, hoping that it will drive the stock down. Carson Block, another activi=
st short seller, =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/33220840.283413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL21hZ2F6aW5lL2F=
yY2hpdmUvMjAyMy8wMy93YWxsLXN0cmVldC1tdWRkeS13YXRlcnMtYWN0aXZpc3Qtc2hvcnQtc2=
VsbGVycy10ZXNsYS1nYW1lc3RvcC82NzI3NzQv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB08022e14" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">describes what he does</a> as =E2=80=98investigative journalism marr=
ied to a different business model=E2=80=99 and is trying to rebrand activis=
t shorts as =E2=80=98journalist investors.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The risks of that model are pretty well known.=
 For one thing, yes, insider trading; some short sellers try to=C2=A0rely m=
ostly on public information to avoid being accused of insider trading.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0For another thing, activist short sellers are=C2=A0<em>constantly=
=C2=A0</em>accused of market manipulation: It is just widely assumed that, =
if you bet against a company=E2=80=99s stock and then=C2=A0publish bad stuf=
f about the company, you are doing something fraudulent and manipulative. I=
f you publish stuff that is=C2=A0<em>wrong</em>, you will get in trouble fo=
r securities fraud: Betting against a stock and then publishing=C2=A0falseh=
oods about the company to drive down the stock is classic fraud, and no one=
 will be sympathetic if you say you made an honest mistake.=C2=A0Even if yo=
u publish stuff that is=C2=A0<em>right</em>, people will be suspicious. The=
re is an ongoing US Department of Justice <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/33220840.283413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29=
tL21hZ2F6aW5lL2FyY2hpdmUvMjAyMy8wMy93YWxsLXN0cmVldC1tdWRkeS13YXRlcnMtYWN0aX=
