adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">PE and rates</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you had asked me a few years ago, at an ext=
remely high level of generality, how much the two tranches of a leveraged b=
uyout should get paid =E2=80=94=C2=A0like, how much interest lenders should=
 charge for lending money to private equity portfolio companies, and how mu=
ch the equity investors in the private equity funds should expect to make =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0I guess I would have thrown out numbers like, I don=E2=80=99=
t know, 7% and 15%? No science to that. But high-yield debt in like the mid=
-to-high single digits, and private equity internal rates of return in the =
low-to-mid teens? Kind of? Blackstone Group Inc., for instance, <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33220840.283413/aHR0cHM6Ly9zM=
jMucTRjZG4uY29tLzcxNDI2NzcwOC9maWxlcy9kb2NfZmluYW5jaWFscy8yMDIzL3EzL0JsYWNr=
c3RvbmUzUTIzRWFybmluZ3NQcmVzc1JlbGVhc2UucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB184b1=
fd3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">lists the investment records</a> for its private equity funds,=
 and many of the more recent ones have those sorts of teen-ish IRRs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then interest rates went up a lot very quickly=
, though. Here is Blackstone founder Steve Schwarzman <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33220840.283413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29=
tL2NvbnRlbnQvODQ0MDljZGUtMTE5Ny00OWM5LWJmODgtZGJlMzcxZTQ0MzEz/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB93d83d6a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">at a conference in September</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf you can earn 12 per ce=
nt, maybe 13 per cent on a really good day in senior secured bank debt, wha=
t else do you want to do in life?,=E2=80=9D Schwarzman told the conference.=
 =E2=80=9CIf you are living in a no-growth economy and somebody can give yo=
u 12, 13 per cent with almost no prospect of loss, that=E2=80=99s about the=
 best thing you can do.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Blackstone, and all the other private equity f=
irms, are now big in private <em>credit</em>, which includes (among other t=
hings) lending money to leveraged buyouts. That used to pay a little; now i=
t pays 12% or 13%. Meanwhile if you work in private=C2=A0<em>equity</em>, a=
nd you got used to mid-teen IRRs, you have a problem. Really two problems:<=
/p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are paying a lot more for debt, w=
hich is going to eat into your returns.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">Even if you do get mid-teen returns, that just doesn=E2=80=99t look v=
ery good compared to earning 13% on the=C2=A0<em>safe=C2=A0</em>tranche of =
the deal.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWhat else do you want to do in life,=
=E2=80=9D says your boss, about private=C2=A0<em>credit</em>, which makes y=
ou nervous about your=C2=A0job in private=C2=A0<em>equity</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a Financial Times article titled =E2=
=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33220840.283=
413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvOGI0YTVkZjYtN2Y2ZC00ODBmLThkMjAtNTU=
3OTM4NTRjMzdl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeabe42ee" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Private equity: hi=
gher rates start to pummel dealmakers</a>.=E2=80=9D It begins like this:</p=
>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In early March, Carlyle Group appeared close t=
o a takeover that valued healthcare software company Cotiviti at $15bn. It =
was just the sort of audacious deal that large private equity firms have be=
en pulling off for much of the past decade.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More than a dozen private lenders, including t=
he credit arms of Blackstone, Apollo Global, Ares and HPS, were ready to si=
gn off on a record $5.5bn private loan that would have put Carlyle in contr=
ol of Cotiviti.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the process dragged on for weeks. Accordin=
g to more than a dozen people involved in the transaction, the key hold-up =
was a stunning setback in an industry managing $3.3tn of assets: Carlyle, o=
ne of the most powerful private equity firms, had been unable to raise all =
of its roughly $3bn equity commitment from investors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The yield on the debt financing, around 12 per=
 cent at the time, would have been approaching the return Carlyle was hopin=
g to earn, stifling interest from potential investors, according to one per=
son involved in the deal. When Carlyle attempted to renegotiate the $15bn v=
aluation, Veritas Capital, the existing private equity owner, walked away f=
rom the sale.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Feels like there is going to be a lot of that.=
</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Oil hedging</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could have an extremely crude<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a>=C2=A0model in which oil drilling companies are long a lot of oil (they=
 own oil in the ground and will need to pump it out over time) and so are e=
xposed to oil price risk; if the price falls they will lose money. Meanwhil=
e oil refiners are short a lot of oil (they use oil to make refined product=
s and so have to buy it over time) and so are exposed to oil price risk fro=
m the other side; if the price goes up they will lose money. (This is an=C2=
=A0<em>extremely=C2=A0</em>crude model, since usually the prices of refiner=
s=E2=80=99 outputs go up when their input prices go up, but just go with it=
.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-10" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tra=
nsparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a>)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This makes oil producers=E2=80=99 and refiners=
=E2=80=99 income volatile, which is risky and makes it hard for them to pla=
n ahead. There are two main ways for them to hedge this risk:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The producers could sell oil futures,=
 and the refiners could buy oil futures. Then they=E2=80=99d lock in prices=
 for the long term, rather than being exposed to volatility in prices.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The producers and the refiners could m=
erge with each other. Then higher prices would be good for one part of the =
business and bad for the other part, and vice versa for lower prices, provi=
ding a natural hedge.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From the perspective of the financial industry=
, the first approach is good for=C2=A0<em>oil derivatives traders </em>(mor=
e trading, more liquidity), while the second approach is good for=C2=A0<em>=
mergers and acquisitions bankers=C2=A0</em>(more deals, more fees). The pen=
dulum has swung, recently, toward the bankers. The <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33220840.283413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2=
NvbnRlbnQvMTRkMDMxYTQtMTBjMy00NzY4LWJjMWYtZjk5ZDlkYjg4ZWE2/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB8890eee5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> Financial Times reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Chevron=E2=80=99s $53bn takeover of renowned o=
perator Hess and ExxonMobil=E2=80=99s $60bn acquisition of shale specialist=
 Pioneer have made oil and gas a rare bright spot for Wall Street=E2=80=99s=
 dealmakers. Merger and acquisition activity in the sector is up 52 per cen=
t so far this year, with more than $260bn in transactions, compared to a 21=
 per cent drop across all industries, according to Refinitiv.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman and Morgan Stanley have been Wall Stre=
et=E2=80=99s biggest beneficiaries, Refinitiv=E2=80=99s data show, with eac=
h working on energy deals worth about $165bn, including transactions they h=
ave worked on together.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Analysts believe that the Exxon and Chevron ac=
quisitions will spark industry-wide consolidation as big oil producers bulk=
 up in a competition to produce the cheapest barrels.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/33220840.283413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMDEvb2lsLW1lcmdlci1tYW5pYS10aHJlYXRlbnMtY3J1ZGUtcy1sa=
XF1aWRpdHktYXMtaGVkZ2Vycy12YW5pc2g_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRt=
X21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMTAxJnV0bV9=
jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBae8fbc95" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Bloo=
mberg News reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The recent wave of dealmaking by US oil produc=
ers =E2=80=94 which may not be finished just yet =E2=80=94 is hastening a d=
ecline in liquidity from the oil market.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hess Corp. and Pioneer Natural Resources Co. h=
ave in recent years bought large derivatives positions to lock in prices fo=
r their future production. Those holdings are set to dry up after the drill=
ers=E2=80=99 takeovers by Chevron Corp. and Exxon Mobil Corp. because super=
majors tend not to hedge, instead using their refining and retail operation=
s as natural buffers against price moves. Two other top hedgers =E2=80=94 D=
evon Energy Corp. and Marathon Oil Corp. =E2=80=94 are also said to have he=
ld merger talks.</p>
</blockquote>
