<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For a long time, there has been demand from in=
vestors for a product that is =E2=80=9CBitcoin, but a US-listed stock.=E2=
=80=9D The most straightforward way to satisfy that demand would be with a =
Bitcoin exchange-traded fund: You put some Bitcoins in a pot, you issue sha=
res of the pot, you let people exchange Bitcoins for shares or shares for B=
itcoins in a way that keeps the price of the shares in line with the price =
of Bitcoin. The US Securities and Exchange Commission, for mostly bad reaso=
ns, has refused to allow anyone to do this. The SEC got sued over this, <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33220840.283413/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMjkvZ3JheXNj=
YWxlLWNhbi1iZS1hLWJpdGNvaW4tZXRmP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9=
tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTEwMSZ1dG1fY2=
FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3c678983" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  and l=
ost</a>, and everyone anticipates that there will soon be Bitcoin ETFs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But for a long time there weren=E2=80=99t, so =
that demand has been=C2=A0satisfied by imperfect substitutes. One substitut=
e is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33220840.2834=
13/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMTUv=
Yml0Y29pbi1ldGZzLWFyZS1hbG1vc3QtaGVyZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTAxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ=
1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzExMDEmdX=
RtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBac7a5002" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  Bitcoin=C2=A0<em>futures=C2=A0</em>ETFs</a>, which are like Bitcoin ETFs =
but use derivatives and have some slippage. Another substitute is the Grays=
cale Bitcoin Trust, which is like a Bitcoin ETF except that you can=E2=80=
=99t take Bitcoins=C2=A0<em>out=C2=A0</em>(you can't trade in your shares f=
or Bitcoins), so the price of the shares does not stay in line with the pri=
ce of Bitcoin. A third substitute is MicroStrategy Inc., a publicly traded =
US software company that also just owns a lot of Bitcoin. It=E2=80=99s a pu=
blicly traded pot of Bitcoin with a software company attached to it, which =
is a sillier way to invest in Bitcoin than just a publicly traded pot of Bi=
tcoin=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>a software company attached, but better th=
an nothing.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-11" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[11]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It seems to me that a lot of these substitutes=
 are lucrative (for the people offering them) but temporary. The most inter=
esting fact about Grayscale is probably that it charges a 2% fee on its pot=
 of Bitcoins. If it converts into an ETF =E2=80=94=C2=A0as it plans to, onc=
e the SEC approves =E2=80=94=C2=A0it probably can=E2=80=99t keep that up; E=
TF fees are much lower, and if Grayscale keeps charging 2%, its shareholder=
s will take their Bitcoins back (as soon as they=E2=80=99re allowed to). An=
d <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33220840.283413/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMDEvc2F5bG9=
yLXMtbWljcm9zdHJhdGVneS1tc3RyLXF1ZXN0aW9ucy1vd24tYml0Y29pbi1wcmVtaXVtLXdpdG=
